 <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.astronautix.com/graphics/m/misland1.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Men in Space<br>
The lunar lander heads for the lunar surface.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
This is one of 3 new EA articles that focus on early space fiction.<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/articles/roastars.htm">Road to the Stars</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> suggests rather unconvincingly that Stanley Kubrick lifted some of the effects for 2001 from a 1954 Soviet film.<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.astronautix.com/graphics/0/2001comp.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
Side-by-side: Soviet <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Road to the Stars</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (left) and Kubrick's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 2001</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (right).<br>
This looks pretty incriminating until you realize that there are only so many ways to portray the standard devices of realistic orbital fiction, like the artificial gravity station and the TV phone. This isn't evidence of a ripoff so much as two directors portraying the same potential reality. <br>
<br>
The third article follows the curious career of the 1939 German short film, <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/articles/theorers.htm"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Space Explorers</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. This was part of the nazi era propaganda effort; though there is little, if any, overt nazi ideology in it. Re-edited, its amazingly advanced special effects sequences became fixtures on 1950s American television.<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.astronautix.com/graphics/m/monstar2.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
Rollout of Weltraumshiff 1 (Spaceship 1) from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Space Explorers</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
